[main.swift](/private/tmp/cmux-stream-codex/main.swift:1) currently does two things:

1. Imports `SwiftUI`.
2. Defines `ContentView`, whose `body` renders a single `Text("Hello")`.

As written, it defines a view but does not define a SwiftUI app entry point, so by itself it is not a complete runnable SwiftUI app target.

**1. App Entry Point**

```swift
import SwiftUI

@main
struct DemoApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView()
        }
    }
}
```

**2. Readability**

```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello")
    }
}
```

This keeps each declaration and view builder on its own line, which scales better once modifiers or child views are added.

**3. #Preview**

```swift
#Preview {
    ContentView()
}
```

A complete cleaned-up version would look like:

```swift
import SwiftUI

@main
struct DemoApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView()
        }
    }
}

struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello")
    }
}

#Preview {
    ContentView()
}
```

